Short:        NTP time sync commodity with timezone support
Author:       Nathan Ollerenshaw <chrome@stupendous.net>
Uploader:     chrome@stupendous.net
Type:         util/time
Version:      1.0.0
Architecture: m68k-amigaos >= 3.2.0
Requires:     AmigaOS 3.2+, bsdsocket.library, Roadshow or similar TCP/IP stack
Distribution: Aminet

SyncTime is a commodity that synchronizes your Amiga's clock with internet
time servers using the SNTP protocol. It features a Reaction-based GUI for
configuration and includes a comprehensive timezone database.

Features:

  * SNTP time synchronization from configurable NTP servers
  * Full IANA timezone database with DST support
  * Region/city timezone picker with 400+ locations
  * Sets TZ and TZONE environment variables
  * Configurable sync interval (minimum 15 minutes)
  * Scrollable activity log
  * Standard commodity hotkey and Exchange integration
  * Runs quietly in the background

Installation:

  Copy SyncTime to your WBStartup drawer or Commodities directory.

  The program will create its configuration file at:
    ENVARC:SyncTime.prefs

Usage:

  SyncTime runs as a standard Amiga commodity. Use Exchange to show/hide
  the configuration window, or press the hotkey (default: ctrl alt s).

  From the configuration window you can:
    - View sync status and last/next sync times
    - Configure the NTP server (default: pool.ntp.org)
    - Set the sync interval in seconds
    - Select your timezone by region and city
    - View the activity log
    - Trigger an immediate sync

  Click "Save" to persist your settings to ENVARC:.

Tooltypes/CLI Arguments:

  CX_PRIORITY=<n>   Commodity priority (default: 0)
  CX_POPUP=YES|NO   Open window on startup (default: NO)
  CX_POPKEY=<key>   Hotkey to toggle window (default: ctrl alt s)

Requirements:

  * AmigaOS 3.2 or later (for Reaction GUI)
  * A working TCP/IP stack (Roadshow, AmiTCP, Miami, etc.)
  * Network connectivity to reach NTP servers

Source Code:

  Source code is available at:
    https://github.com/matjam/synctime

